close_symbols: any helper macros used/expanded by UT_COMPARE_TYPE
explanation:
- UT_COMPARE_TYPE: The switch selector and every case label use this macro. You must know its definition/expansion to determine the numeric values produced for (CompareType, IsUnsigned) and whether some case labels are identical or impossible (i.e. unreachable). Any helper macros used inside its expansion are also required.  
- UtAssert_Compare_t: The type of CompareType. Knowing whether it is an enum or integer and its valid range is required to decide which switch values can actually occur at runtime.  
- UtAssert_Compare_* enumerators (EQ, NEQ, LT, GT, LTEQ, GTEQ, BITMASK_SET, BITMASK_UNSET): The case labels are built from these constants; their numeric values (and ordering) are needed to map case labels to possible runtime values and detect unreachable cases.  
- UtAssert_IntBuf_t: Definition of this union/struct (members .u and .s) is needed to confirm the code in each case is meaningful and to rule out any undefined/illusory duplicate code paths caused by member aliasing or name mismatches (helps validate the intent of signed vs unsigned branches).  
- UT_IntCheck_t: The type of ReferenceValueIn; knowing its underlying type/width/sign matters for understanding possible values fed into UT_COMPARE_TYPE (and for completeness when reasoning about value ranges).  
- bool, true, false (stdbool.h definitions): The switch depends on the IsUnsigned boolean argument and many case labels use literal true/false. Confirming their definitions ensures the macro expansions and comparisons behave as intended (e.g. which integer values represent true/false).  
These symbols together let you determine the exact integer values produced by UT_COMPARE_TYPE for all valid inputs and therefore whether any case labels (or the default) are unreachable per MISRA C’s unreachable-code rule.
